The presence of water content (Eq. (7)) in the transformer oils negatively influences the dielectric characteristics of this insulating liquid and also the insulating solid (paper) [20]. The solubility of water in oil depends essentially on three factors: the temperature, the type of oil (mineral or vegetable), and its condition (new or aged). It varies according to its molecular structure and temperature and has for expression.(7)Ws=Woil.e−BT
Ws: Solubility of water in oil in ppm;
T: Temperature in K;
WoilandB: Constants which depend on the type of oil.

For transformer oils, the dielectric dissipation factor tgδ is directly related to its conductivity and inversely proportional to the product of its static permittivity and the frequency adopted. The tgδ of Eq. (8) measurements were carried out thanks to a bridge assembly [10]. The expression of the tgδ can be shown as follows.(8)tgδ=σ2πfεs
σ: Conductivity;
εs: Static permittivity;
f: Frequency.

With:
e: Charge of the electron;
μ+andμ−: Ion concentration.

The conductivity of the oil is inversely proportional to the power density and is given by the expression.(10)σ=Ej
E: Electrical field;
j: Power density.
